      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Rosenbach_1826-09-29_page02.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                  <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/7900256">
                  Black Castle<lb/>
                     Navan<lb/>
                  </placeName>
                  <date when="1826-09-29"/>Sep<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. 29<hi rend="superscript">h</hi>. 1826</dateline>
               <note place="bottom">[LibNote] Rec[superscript]d[/superscript] Nov 30<lb/>
                  Ans[superscript]d[/superscript] April 20</note>
               <salute>
                  <persName>
                     <!-- Use if letter has a saluation ("Dear Sir," for example). If not, delete this line.-->
                     Dear Sir
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>You must not be surprised with my not being<lb/>
               able to keep up a <add>regular</add> correspondance - I really<lb/>
               have so much to do that I cannot -<lb/>
               I am much obliged by your letter - and thank<lb/>
               you for your <title ref="https://lccn.loc.gov/05020165">essay on Emigration</title> which<lb/>
               I will send to the principal bookseller in<lb/>
               <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/7001306">Dublin</placeName> as you wish it to be reprinted here -<lb/>
               - But further I cannot undertake - <choice>
                  <orig>Booksel
                  lers</orig>
                  <reg>Booksellers</reg>
               </choice> both here and in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/7011781">London</placeName> are at present<lb/>
               disinclined to enter on new publications <add>without being paid for them</add>
               <lb/>
               such <hi rend="underline">has</hi> been &amp; is the general distress in 
               their line of business as in others -<lb/>
               I have been sometime time away from home<lb/>
               &amp; much engaged by the marriage of one<lb/>
               of my sisters - your Essay reached <choice>
                  <orig>Edge-<lb/>
               worths</orig>
                  <reg>Edgeworths</reg>
               </choice> town at a moment when it was <choice>
                  <orig>ab-<lb/>
               solutely</orig>
                  <reg>absolutely</reg>
               </choice> out of my power to read it - As soon<lb/>
               as I return home, I shall read it with<lb/>
               attention - I am at this moment reading<lb/>
               <del>at this <unclear>time</unclear>
               </del> the volume of <title>evidence on<lb/>
                  Emigration from <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/7001181">Ireland</placeName> to the <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/7005685">Canadas</placeName>
                  <lb/>
                  &amp; to various parts of <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/7012149">America</placeName>
               </title> which<lb/>
               was given before the Committee of the<lb/>
               English house of Commons last year -<lb/>
               Emigration is the natural &amp; best<lb/>
               remedy for a redundant population - But<lb/>
               the evils in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/7001181">Ireland</placeName> arise not so much<lb/>
            </p>
            <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Rosenbach_1826-09-29_page03.jpg"/>
            <p>
               from a <hi rend="underline">redundant</hi> as from an <hi rend="underline">unemployed</hi>
               <lb/>
               population - The remedy here wanted<lb/>
               is <hi rend="underline">employment</hi> - <hi rend="underline">demand</hi> for industry<lb/>
               &amp; <hi rend="underline">higher wages for industry</hi> -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>The instances of national <choice>
                  <orig>ingra-<lb/>
               titude</orig>
                  <reg>ingratitude</reg>
               </choice> you mention in your last letter<lb/>
               are very striking - I regret that they
               should have occurred in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/7012149">America</placeName> -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I had admired her gratitude to<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LaFaG1">La Fayette</persName> - But this contrasts sadly<lb/>
                  with her penuriousness to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#JeffT1">Jefferson</persName> - From<lb/>
               this I am afraid there was some love<lb/>
               of <del>theatric</del> display &amp; effect in the <choice>
                  <orig>recep<lb/>
                  tion</orig>
                  <reg>reception</reg>
               </choice> of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LaFaG1">La Fayette</persName> which <add>had</add>] appeared to<lb/>
               me at first the genuine feeling of<lb/>
               enthusiasm honorable to your national<lb/>
               character -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               Do not blame me my dear Sir for<lb/>
               not getting your books republished in<lb/>
               <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/7001181">Ireland</placeName> - It is not from indolence<lb/>
               but from its being totally out of my<lb/>
               power - I thank you for your <choice>
                  <orig>perse<lb/>
                  vering</orig>
                  <reg>persevering</reg>
               </choice> attention to me - And <del>y</del> admire<lb/>
               your persevering benevolence &amp; love of<lb/>
               your country<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               <!--include linebreaks, if used. example: <closer> Yours<lb/> Very sincerely<lb/> -->
               I am truly your obliged<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p>I thank you for the Sketches of <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/7012149">America</placeName> which<lb/>
                  I have just received -</p>
            </postscript>
            <!--You can include a <pb/> here, or inside the postScript.-->
            <!-- Format for postscripts. 
               Postscripts do NOT go inside closer tags. Adjust to take into account the order in your letter. 
